      <section id="our-style">
        <h2>Design Philosophy</h2>
        <p>We design with intention, guided by three principles:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Seasonality:</strong> Choosing stems that are at their peak, locally or regionally, for color and scent.</li>
          <li><strong>Texture:</strong> Mixing structured blooms with airy foliage to create movement and balance.</li>
          <li><strong>Story:</strong> Each arrangement should feel personal — selected with the recipient, space, and moment in mind.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Our aesthetic sits between garden-wild and refined minimalism: loose tapestries of foliage, unexpectedly paired colors, and a focus on stems that perform well in the vase.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="weddings">
        <h2>Weddings &amp; Events</h2>
        <p>We offer collaborative wedding design for couples who want blooms that feel honest and memorable. Below is how we typically work with clients:</p>
        <h3>Our Process</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Initial Consultation:</strong> Discuss style, priorities, guest count, and budget.</li>
          <li><strong>Proposal &amp; Mood Board:</strong> Visual plan with example palettes, focal pieces, and pricing tiers.</li>
          <li><strong>Trial/Mockup:</strong> Optional bouquet trial or centerpiece sample to confirm scale and mood.</li>
          <li><strong>Logistics:</strong> Coordination with venue and vendors for delivery windows, access, and setup.</li>
          <li><strong>Installation &amp; Breakdown:</strong> On-site team manages setup and post-event breakdown if requested.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="note">Tip: Reserve your florist early (6–12 months in peak season) and have a flexible flower list for best pricing and availability.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="care">
        <h2>Flower Care Tips</h2>
        <p>Simple care extends the life of your bouquet. Follow these steps for best results:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cut stems at an angle before placing them in fresh water; re-cut every 2–3 days.</li>
          <li>Change water every 48 hours and clean the vase to reduce bacteria.</li>
          <li>Remove leaves below the waterline to prevent rot.</li>
          <li>Keep arrangements away from direct heat, sunlight, and fruit.</li>
          <li>Use flower food included with the bouquet, or make a home remedy with a small pinch of sugar and a few drops of bleach.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Some blooms — like hydrangea — drink more water, while succulents need very little. If you’re unsure, check the product care card or contact us.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="flowers-quickguide">
        <h2>Quick Guide: Popular Stems</h2>
        <p>Here are a few favorites we use often, what to expect, and symbolic meanings.</p>
        <h3>Roses</h3>
        <p>Durable and versatile. Red = love, white = purity, pink = gratitude. Trim stems and keep cool.</p>

        <h3>Peonies</h3>
        <p>Full, luxurious blooms available in late spring. Handle gently and avoid direct sun.</p>

        <h3>Tulips</h3>
        <p>Bright, modern stems that continue to open in the vase. Trim to control height.</p>

        <h3>Dahlias</h3>
        <p>Dramatic and sculptural; excellent for late-summer arrangements. Provide sturdy support if needed.</p>
      </section>

